Split the dataset into train and test sets

This should be done before binning. Using scorecard::split_df, the bad rate of the dataset is preserved across the train and test sets.

dt_list <- split_df(germancredit_woe.dt, y="creditability", ratios = c(0.8, 0.2), seed = 314)

Evaluate model performance on test set

prediction from a rank-deficient fit may be misleading
metrics <- perf_eva(
  pred=y_pred, 
  label=dt_list$test$creditability, 
  title = 'test',

  show_plot = c('roc', 'f1')

metrics$confusion_matrix$test

auc <- metrics$binomial_metric$test$AUC

The scorecard::perf_eva yields the following:

  1. the optimal threshold (the cutoff probability where the maximum F1 score is attained)
  2. binomial metrics (in our case we only chose to output AIC)
  3. confusion matrix using the optimal threshold
  4. some graphs

Check the scorecard documentation for more details!

Because scorecard::perf_eva does not output the important evaluation metrics we discussed in class, the instructor created functions to do so:

  1. find_optimal_threshold - mimics how scorecard::perf_eva finds the optimal threshold
  2. confusion_matrix - generates the confusion matrix at a certain threshold
  3. get_metrics - calculates the accuracy, precision, sensitivity, specificity, and F1 score at a given threshold
# these are functions that you might want to implement for your Project.
threshold <- find_optimal_threshold(
  pred=y_pred, 
  label=dt_list$test$creditability
  )

#threshold

confusion_matrix(pred=y_pred, 
                   label=dt_list$test$creditability, 
                   threshold=threshold)

metrics_model1 <- get_metrics(pred=y_pred, 
                   label=dt_list$test$creditability,
                   threshold=threshold)

metrics_model1 %>% 
  add_row(metrics='auc', values=auc) %>%
  add_row(metrics='aic', values=aic) ->
  metrics_model1

metrics_model1

Other valuation metrics

  1. Somers D
    • use the InformationValue::somersD() function
  2. Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) Statistic
    • You can use this as an alternative to find the optimal threshold (cut-off probability)
    • specify ks in the binomial_metric parameter of the scorecard::perf_eva() function
  3. Cumulative Accuracy Profile (CAP) and Gini Coefficient
    • specify gini in the binomial_metric parameter of the scorecard::perf_eva() function

Goodness-of-Fit Statistical Test

  1. Hosmer-Lemeshow Test
    • use the ResourceSelection::hoslem.test() function

Variable Selection

This is a creative process. Dont be afraid to experiment! Remember, you are looking for the best subset out of the 2^20 (over a million) total subsets!

A typical starting point for the set of experiments would be:

  1. model1 - full model that uses all the 20 variables
  2. model2 - result of forward selection
  3. model3 - result of backward selection
  4. model4 - result of stepwise selection

Other procedures you should try:

  • removing multicollinear variables (assessed through VIF)
  • removing variables with illogical parameter estimates (\(\beta_m\) is positive)
  • using only the significant variables at a certain level of confidence (p-values are calculated in summary(model))
  • filtering the variables according to their information values
null_model <- glm(creditability ~ 1,

Evaluate the candidate models

evaluate_model <- function(model, dt_list){
  aic <- model$aic
  y_pred <- predict(model, dt_list$test, type="response")

  metrics <- perf_eva(
    pred=y_pred, 
    label=dt_list$test$creditability, 
    title = 'test', 
    binomial_metric = c("auc"), 
    confusion_matrix = TRUE,
    show_plot = c('roc', 'f1')
    )
  
  auc <- metrics$binomial_metric$test$AUC
  
  threshold <- find_optimal_threshold(
                pred=y_pred, 
                label=dt_list$test$creditability
                )
  
  metrics_dt <- get_metrics(pred=y_pred, 
                     label=dt_list$test$creditability,
                     threshold=threshold)
  
  metrics_dt %>% 
    add_row(metrics='auc', values=auc) %>%
    add_row(metrics='aic', values=aic) ->
    metrics_dt
  
  return(metrics_dt)
}

Testing for Multicollinearity

#vif(model1)

vif(model2)

If you run vif(model1), you would get an error There are aliased coefficients in the model. This error arises if there is perfect multicollinearity in the subset of variables. That is, there is at least one variable that is linearly dependent on the other variables. Upon inspection of the coefficients in model1, you can tell that the variable of concern is foreign.worker_woe. This is because there is only one bin for this variable, as seen below. Thus, foreign.worker_woe=0, and it could be expressed as a linear combination of the other variables. To mitigate this, you can try rebinning the foreign.worker variable to have two bins:(1)if the applicant is a foreign worker and (2) if he/she is not.

bins %>% 
  filter(variable =="foreign.worker")

Looking at the vif of the variables in model2, all the vifs are close to 1. Thus, there is no multicollinearity for the subset of variables used for model2.

Scorecard development

Once you have chosen already the best candidate model, you can now transform it into a scorecard format.

card <- scorecard(bins,
          model2,
          points0 = 600, # points at the specified odds
          odds0 = 1/50, # this is the bad/good odds
          pdo = 20, # points needed to double the odds
          )

Using the scorecard in production

scorecard_ply(germancredit, card) %>% View()

Calculate the cutoff score

cutoff_score is an internal R function created by the instructor. Given the optimal threshold, it calculates the corresponding cut-off score for the scorecard.

metrics_model2 %>% 
  filter(metrics=="threshold") %>% 
  select(values) ->
  threshold
# these is a function that you might want to implement for your Project.
cutoff_score <- get_cutoff_score(threshold=threshold, 
                 points0=600, 
                 odds0=1/50, 
                 pdo=20)
cutoff_score

Saving the scorecard

card$basepoints$variable <- "[base points]"
card_list <- lapply(card, function(x) x %>%
                      select(variable, bin, points))
Reduce(function(x, y) merge(x, y, all=TRUE), card_list) %>% 
  write.csv("scorecard_model2.csv", row.names=FALSE)
